00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:37.020
that's ever been done.

00:49:37.020 --> 00:49:39.490
There's over 3,000 now.

00:49:39.490 --> 00:49:43.070
And we've, we think as
accurately as currently can,

00:49:43.070 --> 00:49:45.410
quantified the amount
of every protein family

00:49:45.410 --> 00:49:46.930
and every microbe in them.

00:49:46.930 --> 00:49:50.570
And then we've compared them
across these 3,000 samples,

00:49:50.570 --> 00:49:52.210
some of which have
diseases or are

00:49:52.210 --> 00:49:53.730
from different
parts of the world,

00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:57.450
or different aged individuals
or males versus females.

00:49:57.450 --> 00:50:00.490
We've computed all that
as like a pre-compute,

00:50:00.490 --> 00:50:03.350
and then we've built this tool
so people can search the data

00:50:03.350 --> 00:50:06.480
and just pull out the answers.

00:50:06.480 --> 00:50:09.780
And so, let's see.

00:50:09.780 --> 00:50:10.780
It's a search tool.

00:50:10.780 --> 00:50:12.572
You can search right
here by a gene,

00:50:12.572 --> 00:50:15.030
and we're adding something that
would be more like a Google

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:20.175
search, where you search by a
word, like obesity or enzyme,

00:50:20.175 --> 00:50:22.090
or ABC transporter.

00:50:22.090 --> 00:50:23.120
So we're still working.

00:50:23.120 --> 00:50:25.850
That will be out in
another month or two,

00:50:25.850 --> 00:50:28.360
expanding the
search aspect of it.

00:50:28.360 --> 00:50:31.400
And then here, I think if
I'm online I could show you,

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:33.570
these are just jobs
that have run recently.

00:50:33.570 --> 00:50:36.580
So I can pull up a
job and show you--

00:50:36.580 --> 00:50:39.490
this is in development right
now, so it's not beautiful.

00:50:39.490 --> 00:50:44.410
But someone searched
a gene sequence,

00:50:44.410 --> 00:50:48.860
and then these are things
that we think it might be.

00:50:48.860 --> 00:50:51.210
So these are like possible
annotations of it.

00:50:51.210 --> 00:50:53.550
This is a quantification
of how common

00:50:53.550 --> 00:50:56.520
it is in the human microbiome.

00:50:56.520 --> 00:51:00.610
So people-- some people
have no copies of this

00:51:00.610 --> 00:51:02.520
in their microbiome,
some of the samples,

00:51:02.520 --> 00:51:05.030
and the sample with
the most of this gene

00:51:05.030 --> 00:51:10.330
had 2.3 copies per organism
in their microbiome.

00:51:10.330 --> 00:51:12.940
So they had organisms that had
multiple copies-- on average

00:51:12.940 --> 00:51:15.430
had more than two
copies of this gene.

00:51:15.430 --> 00:51:17.420
So people vary a lot.

00:51:17.420 --> 00:51:19.480
These are some of
the taxa that have

00:51:19.480 --> 00:51:22.470
the gene, some of the
bacteria that are carrying it.

00:51:22.470 --> 00:51:25.180
And then you can
look at associations

00:51:25.180 --> 00:51:26.290
with different traits.

00:51:26.290 --> 00:51:27.610
So let's see if I can find one.

00:51:27.610 --> 00:51:29.330
This is statistically
significant--

00:51:29.330 --> 00:51:30.930
what country you're from.

00:51:30.930 --> 00:51:33.680
So I can click on it.

00:51:33.680 --> 00:51:37.000
And it looks like
this gene is more

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:38.550
common in the
microbiomes of people

00:51:38.550 --> 00:51:42.630
from North America
compared to Europe or Asia.

00:51:42.630 --> 00:51:45.610
So we've precomputed
all of these,

00:51:45.610 --> 00:51:48.610
and these can just be
queried by somebody.

00:51:48.610 --> 00:51:51.840
So that's one of the tools
that we're working on,

00:51:51.840 --> 00:51:54.380
as well as under-the-hood
tools for making

00:51:54.380 --> 00:51:58.300
sure the numbers that go
into these tests are accurate

00:51:58.300 --> 00:52:00.220
qualifications.

00:52:00.220 --> 00:52:02.120
Well, I'm happy to
stick around if anybody

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:03.340
wants to shout afterwards.

00:52:03.340 --> 00:52:04.923
Thank you so much
for the opportunity.

00:52:04.923 --> 00:52:05.840
[APPLAUSE]

